{
  "answer": "**Manu** states that, upon the death of the father and mother, brothers should divide the paternal inheritance **equally**—but with significant privileges for the eldest son, including a special portion of pre-eminence (one-twentieth of the estate plus the best items), an extra share in some cases, and the finest animals and property.[^1][^2]\n\n**Yājñavalkya** affirms that, after the parents' death, sons should divide assets **equally** (and debts too), while allowing a father making a lifetime partition to prefer the eldest or make shares equal—but with no post-mortem privileges mentioned for the eldest.[^3][^4]\n\nYājñavalkya **relaxes** Manu by affirming equal shares as the default after death without the eldest son's extra entitlements (e.g., no automatic special portion or superior items), though both permit paternal favoritism during the father's life.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 9, [p-ec655a](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-ec655a) (Mn_9.104: \"After the death of the father and the mother, the brothers... should divide the paternal inheritance equally\").\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 9, [p-71fc56](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-71fc56) (Mn_9.112–117: eldest gets special portion, best property, extra share).\n\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch. 2, [p-4d6fe3](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-4d6fe3) (Yj_2.114: father may prefer eldest or equalize).\n\n[^4]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, ch. 2, [p-24be00](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-24be00) (Yj_2.117: \"After the death of the parents, the sons should divide the assets and debts equally\").\n\n[^5]: The corpus covers this rule only here; no other works elaborate comparably on sons' post-parental inheritance.",
